snippet.textDisplay: 3:43 It's apparent that Skip never seen the new format at work before. When the limit is time, your main focus is to have more points than the opponent before time expires (which can make it a primarily offensive focus). There's a difference between that and the limit being a target score and the main focus is keeping your opponent from getting there and reaching it before they do (which makes it offensively AND defensively focused). Those target score games tend to be the most intense.
snippet.textOriginal: 3:43 It's apparent that Skip never seen the new format at work before. snippet.textDisplay:
This new ending FORCES the leading team to keep playing offense.
Does it make it less choppy?
No.
Does it make it more exciting and thus more competitive?
Absolutely.
It was a foul-a-thon, but that didn't lessen the quality of play.
It's unfortunate the quality of shooting decreased, but the defense (which is a category that All-Stars SHOULD possess) on display was something that is never showcased in these exhibition style games.
Everyone says 'defense wins championships' and finally, after like 30+ years, defense showed up in an All-star game.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here's why the new format is better:
When there is a target score, you feel like you're always in the game. If the target score is 180 and your team is down 155 - 170, a comeback is possible. But when you're playing against the clock, if there is a min left in the game and you're down 155 - 170, there's a 95% chance you've lost the game.
